#making a map

ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data = world, 
               aes(x = long, 
                   y = lat, 
                   group = group, 
                   fill = region),
               color = "black") +
  guides(fill = FALSE)
## Warning: `guides(<scale> = FALSE)` is deprecated. Please use `guides(<scale> =
## "none")` instead.

#mercator projection (default projection)


ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data = world, 
               aes(x = long, 
                   y = lat, 
                   group = group,
                   fill = region),
               color = "black")+
  theme_minimal()+
  guides(fill = FALSE)+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue"))+
  coord_map(projection = "mercator",
            xlim = c(-180,180))
## Warning: `guides(<scale> = FALSE)` is deprecated. Please use `guides(<scale> =
## "none")` instead.

#sinusoidal projection (circular projection)

ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data = world, 
               aes(x = long,
                   y = lat,
                   group = group, 
                   fill = region),
               color = "black")+
  theme_minimal()+
  guides(fill = FALSE)+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue"))+
  coord_map(projection = "sinusoidal",

# Look at the county data
head(popdata)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   County         Population
##   <chr>               <dbl>
## 1 los angeles      10081570
## 2 san diego         3316073
## 3 orange            3168044
## 4 riverside         2411439
## 5 san bernardino    2149031
## 6 santa clara       1927470
CApop_county<-popdata %>%
  select("subregion" = County, Population)  %>% # selecting both the county and population column 
  inner_join(counties) %>% #renaming county to subregion to join by the counties data set
  filter(region == "california") # some counties have same names in other states
## Joining, by = "subregion"
head(CApop_county)
## # A tibble: 6 × 7
##   subregion   Population  long   lat group order region    
##   <chr>            <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <int> <chr>     
## 1 los angeles   10081570 -119.  34.8   175  7827 california
## 2 los angeles   10081570 -118.  34.8   175  7828 california
## 3 los angeles   10081570 -118.  34.8   175  7829 california
## 4 los angeles   10081570 -118.  34.6   175  7830 california
## 5 los angeles   10081570 -118.  34.6   175  7831 california
## 6 los angeles   10081570 -118.  34.5   175  7832 california
ggplot()+
geom_polygon(data = CApop_county, 
             aes(x = long, 
                 y = lat, 
                 group = group,
                 fill = Population), #using population density as a fill
             color = "black")+
  coord_map()+
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_gradient(trans = "log10") #using logartihmic scale to make easier to visualize

head(stars)
## # A tibble: 6 × 3
##     lat  long star_no
##   <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1  33.5 -118.      10
## 2  35.5 -121.       1
## 3  39.5 -124.      25
## 4  32.9 -117.      22
## 5  33.5 -118.       8
## 6  33.5 -118.       3
ggplot()+
geom_polygon(data = CApop_county, 
             aes(x = long, 
                 y = lat, 
                 group = group,
                 fill = Population),  
             color = "black")+
  geom_point(data = stars, # add a point at all my sites 
             aes(x = long, 
                 y = lat,
                 size = star_no))+ # size proportional to number of stars
  coord_map()+
  theme_void() +
  scale_fill_gradient(trans = "log10")+
  labs(size = "# stars/m2") 

  ggsave(here("Week_7","output","CApop.pdf"))
